Document: EditorDebuggerPlugin
Path: godot/classes/class_editordebuggerplugin.rst
Summary: Base class for creating custom debugger plugins for the Godot editor.

Inherits: RefCounted < Object

The EditorDebuggerPlugin class is the base class for creating custom debugger plugins for the Godot editor. These plugins can extend the functionality of the built-in debugger, allowing for custom inspection and manipulation of game state during debugging sessions.

Key Rule: To create a custom debugger plugin, you must inherit from EditorDebuggerPlugin and implement the necessary methods to interact with the debugger.

This class provides a framework for defining how your plugin integrates with the editor's debugging tools. You can use it to add new panels, custom property editors, or specialized debugging views.

The core functionality of an EditorDebuggerPlugin revolves around responding to debugger events and providing data to the editor. This typically involves overriding methods that are called when the debugger starts, stops, pauses, or when specific objects or properties are inspected.

The EditorDebuggerPlugin class itself does not provide direct UI elements. Instead, it acts as an interface between your custom debugging logic and the Godot editor's debugging interface. You will likely need to use other Godot classes and nodes to build the actual UI for your plugin.

For example, you might create a plugin that visualizes specific data structures, monitors performance metrics in a unique way, or allows for remote debugging of specific game logic. The flexibility of this class allows for a wide range of debugging enhancements.

When developing a plugin, remember to register it with the editor so that it can be loaded and used. The exact mechanism for registration might depend on the Godot version and the plugin's structure, but it generally involves placing the plugin script in the appropriate directory within your project or Godot's addon system.

The EditorDebuggerPlugin is a powerful tool for developers who need more specialized debugging capabilities than what the default debugger offers. By extending this class, you can tailor the debugging experience to your specific project needs.
